To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a slash command (in this case, a `ban` command), follow these steps:

1. First, make sure you have Node.js installed on your machine. If not, download it from https://nodejs.org/ and install it.

2. Create a new directory for your project and initialize it with npm:
```bash
mkdir discord-ban-bot
cd discord-ban-bot
npm init -y
```

3. Install Discord.js and other required packages:
```bash
npm install discord.js @discordjs/slash-command-builder dotenv
```

4. Create a `.env` file to store your bot token:
```ini
DIScord_TOKEN=your_bot_token_here
```

5. Create a `index.js` file for your bot's main logic:
```javascript
const { SlashCommandBuilder } = require '@discordjs/slash-command-builder';
const { Client, Intents } = require 'discord.js';
require 'dotenv'.config();

const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.Guilds, Intents.FLAGS.GuildMessages, Intents.FLAGS.GuildMembers] });

const commands = new SlashCommandBuilder()
  .addCommand((command) =>
    command
      .name('ban')
      .description('Bans a user from the server')
      .option('user', 'The user to ban', 'USER_ID')
      .option('reason', 'The reason for the ban', 'STRING')
      .setPermission(8) // Admin permission
  );

client.commands = commands.toJSON();

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Bot is ready as ${client.user.tag}`);
  client.application.commands.set(commands.toJSON()).then(() => console.log('Commands registered.'));
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const command = client.commands.find((cmd) => cmd.name === interaction.commandName);

  if (!command) return;

  try {
    await interaction.reply({ content: 'Processing...', fetchReply: true });

    const user = interaction.guild.members.cache.get(interaction.options.get('user'));
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason');

    await user.ban({ reason });
    await interaction.editReply(`User ${user.user.tag} has been banned. Reason: ${reason}`);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    await interaction.reply({ content: 'There was an error trying to process your request.', ephemeral: true });
  }
});

client.login(process.env.DIScord_TOKEN);
```

Replace `your_bot_token_here` with your actual bot token. This bot has a `ban` slash command that requires the Admin permission. It takes a user ID and an optional reason as arguments.

6. Run your bot:
```bash
node index.js
```

Now your Discord bot should be online and ready to use the `ban` command. Remember that you'll need to invite the bot to your server and grant it the necessary permissions (Admin) before testing the command.

To create a C++ function that converts markdown-formatted text to HTML, you'll need to use a library for parsing markdown and generating HTML. One popular choice is `cpp-mdl` (C++ Markdown Library) for parsing markdown and `pugixml` for generating HTML. If you don't mind using external dependencies, follow the steps below to set up the project and write the function.

1. First, install the required libraries. For `cpp-mdl`, use vcpkg (https://vcpkg.io/) or follow the instructions on the project's GitHub page (https://github.com/cpplove/cpp-mdl). For `pugixml`, use vcpkg or install it manually (https://pugixml.org/).

2. Create a new C++ file (e.g., `markdown_to_html.cpp`) and include the necessary headers:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include "cpp-mdl/parser.h"
#include "pugixml.hpp"
```

3. Write the function that converts markdown to HTML:

```cpp
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownText) {
    mdl::Parser markdownParser;
    std::string html;
    try {
        auto ast = markdownParser.parse(markdownText);
        pugi::xml_document doc;
        pugi::xml_node root = doc.append_child(pugi::node_declare("html", 5));
        root.append_child(pugi::node_declare("head", 1)).append_child(pugi::node_declare("title", 1).text("Markdown to HTML"));
        root.append_child(pugi::node_declare("body", 1));

        markdownParser.render_html(ast, root);
        html = doc.save();
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << "Error parsing markdown: " << e.what() << std::endl;
        return "";
    }

    return html;
}
```

4. Compile and run the code with your preferred C++ compiler.

Please note that this example assumes you have `cpp-mdl` and `pugixml` installed and properly configured in your development environment. If you encounter any issues, make sure to check the documentation and installation instructions for both libraries.

Keep in mind that this function only converts the markdown text to HTML; it doesn't handle any external resources (images, CSS, JavaScript) or customizations. For more advanced use cases, consider using a dedicated markdown-to-HTML library or a static site generator like Jekyll or Hugo.

